Commentary.Commentary: We are moments away from the action. The players of England are out in the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell are the openers for West Indies. Chris Woakes to start with the ball. Three slips in place and a widish gully...

Pitch Report - Mark Butcher is near the pitch. He says the pitch on Day 2 sees live grass but the pitch has dried out. He is joined by Chris Woakes. He says the ball was doing much and it kept the batters on their toes. Adds that the last wicket stand was huge for them and it was an amazing achievement and they are certainly happy from what they were first. Tells that holding the length will be crucial with the ball. If you overpitch, runs will come but they need to stick to the basics.

Phil Simmons, the West Indies coach, says that he got no problems and adds that they bowled pretty well in the first two sessions. He adds that it gets harder to blast opposition when the ball get softer and credit should be given to two batters in the middle. Adds that he is still happy with the total in the end tells that they need to bat well with the new ball. Mentions that playing all-seam attack was due to the nature of the pitch  and adds that Veerasammy Permaul performance was not as good as they expected from him in the first two games, so they decided to make that change.

Day 2 promises to be yet another riveting day of Test cricket and it all depends on how Windies batters tackle the threat of new ball against the English seam-attack on a pitch with good amount of help for the seamers. Unlike the first two games, this game is likely to be a low-scoring encounter and first innings lead can play a crucial part in this decider. The wicket seems to be easing out a bit as was evident on the latter part of Day 1 and England would like to make the most of the new ball in the first session of Day 2. An interesting first session coming up. Stay tuned.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the third and final Test match of this three-match Test series between West Indies and England. Day 1 turned out to be quite an engrossing one as the wicket had a good amount of life in it and that made the contest between bat and ball, an interesting one. However, English batters failed to show application for the most part of the day and were staring down the barrel at one point in time. However, Windies bowlers who were quite disciplined throughout the day, let the momentum slip away in the final session as the last wicket pair of Jack Leach and Saqib Mahmood added 90 runs.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 …

Right then, this has been an engrossing day of Test cricket! England are back in this game and have momentum on their side now and that makes Day 2 even more interesting. The first ball will be bowled at 7.30 pm IST (2.00 pm GMT). Our coverage though will start well in advance. So do join us for the same. Till then, goodbye and cheers!

West Indies will be gutted with how they have let the advantage slip from their pocket after working so hard and bowling so well throughout the day. The pitch provided them with some help and Windies bowlers were on-target almost throughout the day as they bowled nagging lines and lengths. Kyle Mayers was the one who started the collapse and all other bowlers cashed in. At one point of time, it seemed quite possible that England would be bowled out even under 100 but some very poor body language in the last hour or so of the day with some strange tactics have put West Indies in the spot of bother now. They need to bat well on Day 2 now, as the pitch will aid English bowlers, especially with the new ball and it will be interesting to see how things pan out on Day 2.

However, one cannot forget the poor performance by the English batters and once again, their fragility and over-dependence on Root was exposed on the pitch that has some help for the bowlers. The batters failed to show application that is required on a pitch like this and it was finally the duo of Leach and Mahmood that showed the way and brought them out of the jail in the final session. It would have been much worse for them and the batters need to pull their socks up and now it will be interesting to see how their bowlers go about their business on this pitch.

What a day of Test cricket! Take a bow, Jack Leach and Saqib Mahmood. England were down and out but this partnership has taken them to safer shores now. They were 90-8 at one point in time and are now looking in a decent position with more than 200 on the board. This is what Test cricket is all about, it is tough and one cannot put the foot off the paddle at any stage. West Indies were lacklustre as the final wicket partnership started frustrating them and all credit should be given to Leach and Mahmood for showing the grit and fight when their team needed it the most.

Would you believe it, West Indies finally get a wicket off the last over of the day. England have been bowled out for 204 but not before we have seen history been made by the last wicket pair of Saqib Mahmood and Jack Leach!

OUT! CHOPPED ON! Finally, West Indies get the wicket. A floated ball, on a length and outside off. Saqib Mahmood tries to hoick it on the leg side but gets a bottom edge and it ricochets onto the stumps. What a superb innings it was from Mahmood and from Leach as well. One to remember for a long time. England are all-out on 204 and that will be Stumps on Day 1.

The pace attack of West Indies continue to do their incredible job. They took the wicket of Stokes, right at the beginning of the session and their discipline bowling attack was rewarded with the middle-order wickets. Interestingly, Kyle Mayers was not seen after his first spell, right at the start. But as of now, the host did not require much of his service. West Indies will hope they take the remaining two wickets as soon as possible. Join us back in a short while for the final session.

Jayden Seales is up for a quick chat. He says that it is a bit of fun to bowl here with some grass and movement. He adds that they wanted to stick with their plans and be consistent because there is some movement in the pitch. He mentions that the pitch has got a little better to bat on but it is about sticking to their plans.

A yorker now, on middle. Leach digs it out to covers.
Full and outside off. Leach misses his defense.
Dropped! Very full and outside off. Leach looks to punch it but the ball takes the outside edge and Kyle Mayers at first slip juggles but fails to hold the ball.
Length and outside off. Leach leaves it alone.
Around off this time, pushed to covers.
A length ball, outside off. Leach looks to defend but the ball nips away and gets beaten on the outside edge.
Leg bye! Down the leg side again. Leach misses his tuck. It goes off the pads and to square leg for a leg bye.
FOUR! Given off the bat! A length ball, down the leg side. Leach seems to miss his flick. The ball races away to the fine leg fence. Yes, it took gloves and there is nothing keeper can do about it.
Length and outside off. Leach shuffles across and leaves it alone.
Touch fuller and on off. Blocked out.
Length and outside off. Leach keeps it out.
Fuller ball, straightening on the pads. Woakes flicks it hard and to deep mid-wicket. The fielder from deep square leg gives a long chase and stops the ball with his boot, saves a run.
Length ball, outside off. Leach walks across just to watch the ball sail pass by.
Full ball, outside off. Leach prods and shoulders arms to it.
Length and outside off. Leach swings across and misses.
A length ball, around off. Leach looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the front pads.
Very full and on middle, flicked to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Outside off, on a length. Woakes guides it to point.
Alzarri Joseph (10-4-20-2) is back on.
Fuller and outside off from around the wicket. Leach plays it back to Holder.
Length and outside off, pushed to covers.
Again defends with soft hands and the outside edge goes to gully this time.
Length and on off. Leach tries to defend with soft hands but gets an outside edge, and the ball stays low to fourth slip.
On middle, kept out.
FOUR! Good partnership building here! Fuller and outside off. Leach drives it through covers for a boundary. 100 up for England.
A yorker, on middle. Woakes squeezes it out to mid on.
Length ball, outside off. Woakes shoulders arms to it. The ball is not doing much now.
On a length and on off. Woakes works it to covers.
FOUR! Valuable runs! Length and outside off. Woakes punches it through covers for a boundary.
Short in length, outside off. Woakes withdraws his bat at the very last moment.
A length ball, on off. Leach defends with an angled bat, through gully for a single.
Shorter and outside off. Woakes flashes at it and misses.
Length and on middle. Woakes dead bats it.
A full ball, outside off. Leach puts a big stride forward and pushes it to covers for a single.
On middle, Leach works it to square leg.
Beauty! A length ball, angling outside off. Leach looks to defend inside the line, misses.
Angles it on the pads, tucked to square leg for a single.
Jason Holder (6-3-9-0) is back into the attack.
This was short and outside off. Leach taps it on the up and to point.
Jaffa! Short of a length, angling outside off. Leach tries to defend on his toes but gets beaten on the outside edge.
A length ball, angling on middle. Leach hangs back to defend.
Another solid block from Leach.
A length ball, angling on middle. Blocked out.
Jack Leach is the next man in.

OUT! TIMBER! That is a ripper from Roach and confusion on the face of Overton! Why not? West Indies are bossing this session. This is on a length and just outside off. It lands and nips back in sharply. Craig Overton is squared up as he looks to defend and he gets beaten on the inside edge. The ball goes through the gate and clips the stumps. Nothing Overton can do about it.

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, down the leg side. Woakes misses his flick. Holder at slips was the only one interested as he appealed and no one joined him in the action. The replay shows there was no bat.
Again down the leg side. Woakes misses his whip.
A full ball, outside off. Woakes looks to drive but gets a thick outside edge to gully. Good stop there.
This one slides down the leg side. Woakes misses his flick.
Touch fuller and outside off. Woakes defends it out.
A length ball, around off. Overton defends it late and it takes the inside edge to square leg for a single.
Jayden Seales will continue.
Short of a length, steep bounce, outside off. Woakes lets it through.
Length again, on off. Woakes leans and blocks it out.
Angles a length ball, around off. Defended out.
FOUR! A length ball, way outside off. Woakes slaps it through covers for a boundary.
A  length ball, outside off. Woakes leaves it alone.
Fuller ball, on middle, pushed to mid on.

Drinks! West Indies are breathing fire at the moment and they are all over the visitors. 4 wickets have fallen since the start of this session and if this partnership does not work, there is full chance of England bundling out in the next hour or so. Kemar Roach (9-2-20-1) is back on.
Back of a length, around off and shaping away from the batter. Craig Overton leaves it alone.

FOUR BYES! Drifts down the leg side this time. Craig Overton looks to flick it but misses. Joshua Da Silva behind the stumps dives to his left to stop it but fails. It races away towards the long leg fence for a boundary.
Low bounce this time. On a good length, outside off. Craig Overton looks to push it away but the ball seams away and beats him.
Seales goes for a full delivery, around off. Craig Overton drags it from around off towards right of mid on for a couple.
Lands it on a good length, outside off. Craig Overton leaves it alone.
Goes fuller on middle. Craig Overton works it through mid-wicket for a couple.
Back of a length, on middle. Craig Overton defends it towards mid on for a single.
On a length, on middle. Craig Overton works it through mid-wicket for a couple.
FOUR! Short and wide outside off. Craig Overton throws his bat at it and gets a thick outside edge. The ball flies over the slip fielder for a boundary. Windies will not mind this.
On a length and down the leg side. Craig Overton looks to clip it but misses.
Goes fuller around off. Chris Woakes goes for a big booming drive. He gets a thick outside edge and the ball goes through the gully region to third man for a single.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Chris Woakes leaves it alone.
Another play and a miss! On a good length, outside off. Craig Overton keeps his bat inside the line of the ball this time.
A good-length delivery outside off and it seams away nicely again. Craig Overton pushes at it tentatively but the ball beats him.
A thick outside edge. On a good length, around off. Craig Overton drives but gets a thick outside edge. The ball goes through the cover-point region for a couple.
Ohh...almost a wicket! This time a beautiful away swing! Fullish delivery, outside off. Craig Overton drives it away from his body and the ball beats the outside edge of his blade.
Craig Overton is the new man in.

OUT! KNOCKED HIM OVER! Seven down now and England are in danger of getting bowled out inside two sessions now. This one is pitched on a good length again but on the off stump line and it nips back in. Ben Foakes is completely surprised by the seam movement there and gets beaten off the inside edge of his blade. The ball knocks over the middle pole and England sink further. Can Windies bowled them out under 100?
Commentary.Howout: b Jayden Seales

Commentary.Commentary: Lands it on a good length but way too outside off to make the batter play there. Ben Foakes leaves it alone.
On the shorter side again, outside off. Woakes goes for the cut shot but misses it.
Bangs this one short on off. Chris Woakes ducks under it.
On a length, on off. Chris Woakes blocks it out.
Back of a length, around off. It seams away again but it is well outside off. Woakes lets it go.
Jaffa! On a good-length around off. Chris Woakes looks to defend it from his crease but the ball seams away and beats the outside edge of his blade.
Back of a length, outside off. There is width and Chris Woakes has a tentative slash at it but gets beaten.
Fullish delivery on middle. Ben Foakes looks to drive but gets the inside half of his blade to square leg.
Another delivery that lands on a length and it outside off. Ben Foakes lets it go again.
On a good length, outside off. Ben Foakes leaves it alone.
FOUR! A rare bad delivery and Ben Foakes takes full advantage of it. Drifting on the pads, around leg. Ben Foakes flicks it towards the backward square leg region for a boundary.
On a length, on middle. Ben Foakes works it towards the leg side.

Starts with a fuller delivery, around off and with some late movement away from the batter. Chris Woakes looks to defend but the ball catches the outside edge of his blade and falls short of the third slip fielder.
Angling into the body, on the shorter side. Ben Foakes tucks it fine towards long leg for a couple.
On a length and angling into middle and leg. Foakes works it towards the leg side.
In that channel, around off. Ben Foakes leaves it alone watchfully.
Goes slightly shorter around off. Ben Foakes lets it go.
Back of a length, around off. Ben Foakes defends it towards the off side.
A good-length delivery, outside off. Ben Foakes leaves it alone.
Goes straighter, on off. Chris Woakes blocks it out.
On a good length and outside off. Chris Woakes leaves it alone comfortably.
FOUR! Nicely played. Roach serves a fullish delivery around off. Chris Woakes leans forward and drives it through covers for a lovely boundary.
On a length, on middle. Ben Foakes clips it to fine leg for a single.

Another huge apppeal but the umpire is not interested. West Indies decide to not take a review. Back of a length, on off and it nips back in. Ben Foakes looks to defend it from his crease but the ball beats him and hits him on the pad. There is an appeal but the umpire says no and rightly so and the replays show that it is missing stumps.
Goes fuller on off. Ben Foakes drives it back to the bowler.
On a length, on off. Chris Woakes blocks it out.
On a length and outside off. Woakes leaves it alone.
Back of a length, around off. Chris Woakes steers it towards the deep backward point region for a couple.
Woakes joins Foakes in the middle.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Another one bites the dust! What a delivery this is from Alzarri Joseph. After taking the ball into Jonny Bairstow in the last delivery, he takes this one away from him. On a good length around off. Jonny Bairstow is stuck on his crease and looks to defend it. The ball takes the outside edge of his blade and Joshua Da Silva behind the stumps takes another catch. This is all falling apart for England now, they need some sort of partnership now to bring some stability to the innings.
Commentary.Howout: c Joshua Da Silva b Alzarri Joseph

Commentary.Commentary: Beats him all ends up now! Back of a length, around off and it nips back in sharply. Jonny Bairstow looks to defend but the ball beats the inside edge of his blade and goes through to the keeper.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Jonny Bairstow leaves it alone.
On a length, on off. Ben Foakes looks to defend it off the front foot but gets the inside edge onto his pads.
Ben Foakes comes in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! This time no hesitation from the umpire as there is clear edge and Lees walks back after a gritty little innings. Roach with that angle from 'round the wicket, pitching it on a good length, around off. It straightens again after pitching and this time it catches the outside edge of the blade of Alex Lees as he looks to defend it. The ball goes behind the stumps to the keeper. Joshua Da Silva and takes an easy catch. Half of the side back to the pavilion now.
Commentary.Howout: c Joshua Da Silva b Kemar Roach

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, around off. Lees pushes it towards the off side.

Huge appeal for caught behind but the umpire turns it down. Goes fuller, outside off. Lees goes for a drive off the front foot but gets beaten off the outside edge. However, there is noise as the ball goes past his blade and there is a huge appeal. The umpire says no and Windies do not take a review.
Roach comes 'round the wicket and lands it on a length, around off. Lees looks to defend it but the ball straightens and beats the outside edge of his blade.
On a good length and angling across Lees. He leaves it alone.
Jonny Bairstow walks out.

OUT! CAUGHT and BOWLED! Big wicket this, as Stokes makes his way back to the pavilion. England lose their fourth and sink further. Alzarri Joseph goes short around off. Stokes looks to pull it but gets the bottom of his blade. The ball goes right of Alzarri Joseph and he takes a sharp catch off his own bowling. Good reflexes shown by the fast bowler and Windies continue to chip in with wickets.
Commentary.Howout: c & b Alzarri Joseph

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length, around off. Stokes punches it to covers.

This time he finds the outside edge but the ball falls short of the slip fielder. Goes slightly fuller and serves it on a good length, on off. Stokes looks to defend but the ball catches the outside edge of his blade and falls short of the second slip fielder.
On the shorter side around off. Stokes defends it off the back foot towards the off side.
Contines with a back-of-a-length delivery, on off. Stokes with a solid block again.
Back of a length, on off. Stokes is right behind it and blocks it.
Full and on off. Lees mistimes his push back to the bowler.
Full outside off and shaping more away. Left alone.
A bit closer to the off stump but not much for Lees to get his blade in between. Another leave.
Touch fuller and outside off. Lees shoulders arms to it.
Length ball, this one nips back in sharply. Lees looks to defend but gets hit on the pads.

FOUR! Almost chopped on! A length ball, outside off. Lees looks to drive but it takes the inside edge and goes past the leg stump for a boundary. Roach has a smile on his face, he knows it was very close.
Short of a length, angling across. Stokes on the back foot tries to punch it but misses. Good end to the over by Joseph.
On the pads this time. Lees bunts it to deep square leg for a run.
A length ball, way outside off. Lees offers no shot to that one.
Fullish delivery, sliding outside off. Lees watches it go through to the keeper.
Touch fuller this time, on middle. Stokes turns it to square leg and takes off for a quick single.
On a length and on middle. Stokes defends right under his eyes.
Alzarri Joseph to start from the other end.
A length ball, angling on middle. Lees hangs and blocks it.
Full and on off. Lees leans and blocks it.
Full ball, outside off. Lees shoulders arms to it.
Length ball, outside off. Stokes punches off the back foot through covers for a single.
Length ball, outside off. Stokes is happy to leave it alone.
A length ball, from around the wicket on middle. Stokes pushes it to mid on.

We are back for the afternoon session! West Indies players are out there in the middle. Alex Lees and Ben Stokes are also in the middle to resume their innings. Kemar Roach will start with the ball for West Indies. Here we go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 …

Right then, the first session has been dominated by the Windies seamers. However, they need to keep the good work going as the wicket has some spice in it and has enough help for the seamers. England batters have a tough task ahead of them and it will be interesting to see how they go about their business in the afternoon session. Stay tuned as we will back at 10.10 pm IST (4.40 pm GMT) for the second session.

Kyle Mayers is up for a quick chat. He says that he was sticking to his plans and was mixing in between and all came off according to the plans. On the wicket of Root, he tells that he is happy to take the big wicket. Informs there was seam early on and the ball is moving and he hopes that the wicket stays the same and changes tomorrow.

Root is the pillar of this English side and once you get that man for a duck, more often than not you will see this English batting unit struggling. It has been the case this morning as this fresh pitch provided good help for the seamers and Zak Crawley played a loose shot going for an expansive drive away from his body. Root could not trouble the scorers and with the in-form Dan Lawrence also back in the hut, England need Lees and Stokes to show more character and fight in the middle session.

Windies skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite elected to bowl first having opted for an all-pace attack on a greenish looking pitch. His bowlers didn’t disappoint him either as they bowled nagging lines and lengths to trouble English batters on a regular basis. However, the star of the show was the man who is playing his first Test match of the series, Kyle Mayers. He bowled five maidens in a row and got two wickets on the way, including a big one of English skipper, Joe Root. Jayden Seales then came back for his second spell in the latter part of the session and got rid of Dan Lawrence to make sure that the pressure is on England going into the Lunch break.

46 runs in 27 overs with three wickets in the first session of this final Test match! Windies will surely go back as the happier side into the break. However, the most pleasing aspect for every Test cricket lover out there is that the pitch promises to provide better balance between the bat and ball and if first session is anything to go by, we are in for some engrossing cricket.
On a length, on middle. Lees blocks it out. That will be Lunch on Day 1.
Full ball, slanting outside off. Lees leaves it.
Another good leave from Alex Lees.
Outside off, on a length. Lees shoulders arms.
Beauty! On a length, just around off. Lees looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge and the ball is inches away from knocking the off pole.
A length ball, shaping away, outside off. Kept out.
Short in length, on off. Stokes hops and blocks it.
Length ball, close to the off stump. Stokes shoulders arms to it.
Length and way outside off. Left alone.
Length again, on off. Stokes is hurried as he defends this.
A  length ball, way outside off. Stokes leaves it alone.
Ben Stokes walks in at number 5.

OUT! LBW! Dan Lawrence is given LBW but after consulting his partner, he takes it upstairs. UltraEdge shows no bat there. Ball Tracking shows three reds and Dan Lawrence's lazy stay has been cut off. He did not look much confident while batting. Seales steams and serves it full and angling around middle and leg. Dan Lawrence misses his flick. The only thing which would save Lawrence was the angle but the umpire thinks otherwise and raises his dreaded finger. Lawrence still takes it upstairs but burns the review. West Indies right on top at the moment.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Jayden Seales

Commentary.Commentary: A length ball, on middle, Lawrence clips it to mid-wicket for a single.
Outside off, tapped to point.
On a length and outside off. Lawrence prods and keeps it out.
BEATEN! A stifled appeal follows for caught behind. On the driving-length, outside off, it moves away a bit after landing. Lawrence looks to drive but misses.
Length and outside off, nipping back in. Lawrence shoulders arms to that.
A length ball, outside off. Lawrence drives it through point for a couple of runs.
Fuller this time, on off, pushed to covers. Consecutive maidens.
Short in length, on middle. Lees defends it out on the deck.
Outside off. Left alone.
Superb delivery! A length ball, around off, it lands and jags back and hits Lees on the pads as he gets surprised by the movement. He losses his balance and almost falls down on the deck.
A length ball, outside off, hint of away shape there. Lees looks to block it but misses.
West Indies bowlers are still getting good amount of movement. A length ball, angling on middle, defended on the leg side.
This one nips back in sharply, around middle, there is extra bounce as well. Lawrence plays all around it and gets hit high on the pads. A maiden over.
A length ball, outside off, not much movement there. Lawrence looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Way outside off. Left alone.
Length ball at 137 clicks, around off. Lawrence dead bats it.
Fuller and on off. Defended out.
A length ball, outside off, shaping in. Lawrence lets it through to the keeper.
FOUR! A length ball, outside off. Lees tries to defend with hard hands. The ball takes the outside edge and goes past the gully fielder for a boundary.
Wow! That ball just whizzed past the off stump. Fullish ball, outside off and it just seams back in sharply. Lees shoulders arms to it and the ball stirs past the off stump by inches.
Short in length, angling around off. Lees looks to defend but misses.
Pitches it up, and on off. Lees leans and blocks it out.
Full, outside off and hint of away movement there. Lawrence drives it through covers for a single.
This one lands outside off and seams away. Lawrence shoulders arms to it.
Length ball, outside off. A backfoot punch from Lees but straight to point.
Short of a length, on off. Lees hangs back as he defends with soft hands. It takes the inside edge and deflects onto the pads.
Comfortable three runs! Fuller, straight on the pads. Lawrence flicks it past mid-wicket and collects three runs.
Length and on middle. Dan blocks it out.
Four byes! A length ball, this one lands on middle and swings way down the leg side. Lawrence misses his tuck. The keeper cannot do much and it races away to the fence.
A length ball, on off. Lawrence steps across and tucks it to square leg.
Alzarri Joseph is brought into the attack.
This time a fullish delivery on middle. Lees drives it to mid on now.
Lands on the off stump line and on a length. The ball comes in sharply into Lees as he looks to flick it but misses. The ball hits high on the pads of Lees but going down leg and too high.
Pitches this one around off. The ball nips back into the batter. Lees defends it towards the leg side.
This time drfting on the pads. Lees works it slightly uppishly towards square leg but well short of the fielder.
Back of a length again, on middle. Dan Lawrence works it to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length, around off. Dan Lawrence blocks it out.
Jayden Seales is back on. Meanwhile, Kyle Mayers walks straight to the pavilion. Might just need some rest...
Yes, he does! Five maidens in the row for Mayers! Back of a length, around off. Lees goes back and looks to push it towards the off side but gets the inside edge onto the pads.
Back of a length, around off. Lees pushes it towards the off side off the back foot. Still not a single run conceded by Mayers, can he bowl another maiden?
On a length and angling into the batter. Lees leaves it alone watchfully.
On a good length, outside off. Lees leaves it alone this time.
Beats the outside edge of this blade yet again! This is on a good length, around off. Lees presses forward to defend but the ball beats the outside edge of his blade as it straightens after pitching.
On a length, outside off and coming back into Lees. He leaves it alone watchfully.
Lands on a length again, closer to the off pole. Dan Lawrence defends it off the front foot.
Serves it on a length, outside off. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone.
Full, on off. Dan Lawrence drives it to covers without much timing.

Beautifully bowled! This is around off and on a length and that entices the batter to come forward. Dan Lawrence pushes forward to defend but the ball seams away and beats the outside edge of his blade.
Goes slightly fuller on off. Dan Lawrence drives it but gets the inside half of his blade to square leg.
Hits the length hard, outside off. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone.
Full delivery and a bit too wide this time. Lees leaves it alone watchfully.
Goes fuller again, outside off. Lees leaves it alone this time.

Well bowled! This is a fullish delivery around off and swinging away. It entices the batter to drive as Lees tries to drive it through covers. The ball beats the outside edge of his blade and goes through to the keeper.
On a good length, outside off. Lees leaves it alone.
Serves on a length again, around off. Lees is solid on his defence.
Lands on a length, on off. Lees blocks it out.

NOT OUT! West Indies lose their review! Holder lands this fuller on middle and it nips back in. Dan Lawrence looks to defend it but misses. The ball hits his pads and there is an appeal. The umpire though is not interested. Kraigg Brathwaite takes his time and then takes a review. The replays roll in and the UltraEdge shows no bat involved. The Ball Tracker shows that the ball is missing stumps. So the original decision stays and Dan Lawrence will continue.
Review taken. Holder convinces Kraigg Brathwaite to take the LBW decision upstairs. No bat there. Ball Tracking shows wickets missing and West Indies have lost two reviews now.
Near the off stump again, on a length at 126 kph. Dan Lawrence defends it out.
Lands on a length, on off. Dan Lawrence blocks it off the front foot.
Another fullish delivery, outside off. It swings away a tad. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone.
A fullish delivery on off. Lees looks to drive it towards the off side but gets the inside edge of his blade to square leg for a single.
Good-length delivery, around off. Lees leaves it alone.
Goes fuller on off. Dan Lawrence drives it to mid on.
Dan Lawrence is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! What an inspired selection this is already proving out to be! What a delivery, yet again by Mayers! He gets the big fish now. Lands on a good length, around off. Root is stuck on his crease and looks to defend. The ball seams away a bit after pitching and catches the outside edge of Root's blade. The ball goes back to Joshua Da Silva behind the stumps and he takes an easy catch to send back the English skipper on his way. Two quick wickets and Windies are right on the top now.
Commentary.Howout: c Joshua Da Silva b Kyle Mayers

Commentary.Commentary: Good-length delivery, outside off and seaming away. Root leaves it alone.
Tight line again, on a length near the off pole. Root defends it solidly yet again.
Lands on a length, on off. Root is right behind it to block it.
Back of a length, around off. Root defends it towards the off side off the back foot.

Drinks! So far, the host will be happy with the first hour of play. One wicket while giving away just 29 runs and they are bowling with probing lines and lengths as well. England, on the other hand, needs these two to bat for as long as possible and go unhurt to the end of this session.
FOUR! This time a shot of authority! Holder goes fuller again but a bit too straight this time, on middle. Lees flicks it through the mid on region for a boundary.
Goes fuller on off.  Lees drives it towards the off side. Roach moves to his left from short cover and stops it with a dive.
Drifts on the pads now. Lees works it towards the fine leg region and gets a couple.
Ohh...another one that nips back in sharply. Lands around off and it comes into Lees. He looks to drive it away but misses and the ball hits his pads. It is however, going down leg.
On a good length, outside off. Lees lets it go.
On a length and angling into off. Lees blocks it from his crease.
A peach of a delivery to end the over! Fullish delivery, around off. Root leans forward and looks to drive it but the ball straightens and beats the outside edge of his blade to beat Root completely.
Back of a length, around off. Root rides the bounce and defends it towards the off side.
Serves this on a good length, on off. Root blocks it out.
On a length, outside off. Root leaves it alone.
Joe Root, the skipper walks out at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT! Kyle Mayers strikes and the Windies get their first wicket. Loose, very loose from Zak Crawley and a sharp catch from Kraigg Brathwaite to send back the English opener back to the hut. Lands on a length, around off and it is a cross-seam delivery. Zak Crawley goes for a big booming drive on the up and ends up hitting it straight to short cover. The ball hits high on his bat and Kraigg Brathwaite takes a sharp catch. So an early wicket for Windies and this pitch surely has more life than what we saw in the previous games.

Commentary.Commentary: Lands on a length, outside off. Zak Crawley lets it go.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Lees leaves it alone.

ohh...this goes over the stumps! It lands on a good length, outside off and nips back in sharply as Holder comes 'round the wicket. Lees leaves it alone and the ball comes back into him and goes over the stumps back to the keeper.
Back of a length, around off. Lees goes back and blocks it out.
Goes straight this time. On a length, on middle and leg. Lees looks to flick it but misses. The ball hits his pads but it is going down leg, so no appeal from the bowling side.

Good-length delivery and going across Lees, outside off. He leaves it alone watchfully.
Back of a length, around off. Zak Crawley rides the bounce and defends it towwards the off side. Mayers starts with a maiden!
Kyle Mayers is struggling with his run-up. Pulled out two times before delivering the ball.

Zak Crawley walks down the pitch this time. This is delivered on a length, outside off. Zak Crawley leaves it alone. The bowling has been tight and Zak Crawley was looking to make something out of this good-length delivery.
Goes slightly shorter on off. Zak Crawley stays deep in his crease and defends it.
On a good length, on off at 126 kph. Zak Crawley blocks it off the front foot.
Pulls his length back a little, outside off. Zak Crawley leaves it alone.
Starts with a fullish delivery around off. Zak Crawley drives it to short cover.
Kyle Mayers is into the attack now. Two slips and a gully in place.
Touch fuller and on middle. Crawley helps it away to deep square leg for a single. Good start so far by England.
On a length, outside off. Crawley offers no shot.
Length and outside off. Left alone.
A length ball, drifting around leg. Crawley looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the pads.
A length ball, on middle. Lees knocks it to covers and takes off for a quick single. A direct hit at the non-striker's end but Lees made his ground on time.
BEATEN! A length ball, swinging away outside off. Lees looks to play at it but the angle was always going away.
A full ball, around off. Crawley looks to defend on the front foot but gets an inside edge onto the pads. Roach walks away with a big smile.
Tad fuller, sliding around off. Crawley prods and dead bats it.
Length ball, shaping away outside off. Zak leaves it alone.
Too straight this time, on the pads. Lees wrists it through mid-wicket for three runs.
Length ball, angling on middle from around the wicket. Lees leans and defends it.
Angling on the pads, it is nudged to square leg for a single.
Length and on off. There is a hint of inward movement. Lees defends it out. An eventful over from Holder. Maiden as well.
This one is near the 4th stump channel, on a good-length. Lees watchfully leaves it.
A full ball, outside off. Lees now tries to drive this but misses. Superb start from Holder.
A fuller ball, outside off and going away with the angle off the deck. Lees plays across the line and misses.
Length and on off. Blocked out.
A beauty to start with! A length ball, angling around off and jags back in sharply. Lees shoulders arms to it but the movement makes the ball hit him on the pads.
First bowling change of this final Test match. Jason Holder replaces Jayden Seales.
Another length ball, outside off. Crawley gets forward and shoulders arms to it.
This is outside off. Crawley covers his stumps and lets it through.
Touch fuller, angling around off. Crawley lunges and keeps it out.
Length ball, outside off. Crawley shoulders arms to it.
This one stays very low! Length ball, outside off, the ball dies after landing. Crawley again tries to defend but the ball rolls under his bat.
Roach has been good so far! A length ball, outside off. Crawley comes forward to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Drags his length back, around off. Lees drops it to covers.
FOUR! A length ball, way outside off. Lees cuts it past point. Blackwood gives a chase and stops it from his boots but the ball had enough momentum to still touch the cushion.
Length ball, outside off. Alex lets it through to the keeper.
Full and down the leg side. Lees misses his flick. Joshua Da Silva, the keeper does well to get a hand to it and stop it.
FOUR! Well timed! This is short and on middle. Lees pulls it gently to mid-wicket and the ball races away to the fence.
Full, slanting way outside off. Lees leaves it alone.
A length ball, outside off. Crawley has a tentative poke at it and misses.
FOUR! First boundary of the innings! Pitched up, on middle. Crawley drives it past the diving mid on fielder for a boundary.
Outside off. Left alone.

NOT OUT! A length ball, around the 5th stump channel, it lands and nips back in sharply. Crawley looks to shoulder arms but the ball jags back in and hits him high on the pads. An appeal follows for LBW but the umpire is not interested. West Indies take the review. No question of impact as no shot was offered. Ball Tracking shows wickets missing by a quiet mile.

Review! West Indies have taken a review for LBW against Zak Crawley. He has offered no shot. The replays roll in and the Ball Tracker shows that the ball is missing stumps. So the original decision stays and Zak Crawley will continue.
Length ball, outside off. Crawley on the front foot, defends with soft hands.
Fuller and on middle. Crawley steps across and nudges it to square leg. A watchful start for England.
On the pads, Lees tucks it to square leg.

Leg bye! A huge shout for LBW but not given! This was very close. A full toss, slanting on the pads. Crawley misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. An appeal but might be going down and Kraigg Brathwaite does not review for it. A leg bye taken.
Length ball, but this time was way outside off. Crawley offers no shot.
Length ball, coming with an angle, just outside off. Crawley tries to defend inside the line and misses.
Length and angling on off. Blocked out.
Beauty! Hits the deck hard, on a length and this one moves away off the seam. Crawley gets tall to defend but gets beaten by the away movement. The ball was very close to kissing the outside edge.
Very full and on off, pushed to covers. Roach is yet to find that probing line.
This is well outside off, on a length. Lees with an easy leave.
Length ball from around the wicket, outside off. Left alone.
Zak Crawley is underway! Back of a length, on middle. Zak Crawley works it to mid-wicket for a single.
Lands on a length again, around off. Zak Crawley leans forward and defends it.
This time it nips back off the surface. On a length, around off and it comes back into the batter. Zak Crawley defends but gets the inside edge onto his pads.
Pulls his length back and serves this around off. Lees pushes it towards the off side without much timing.
Fullish delivery on off. Lees drives it through covers for a couple.
An appeal for caught behind but not given! Short of a length, on off. Lees looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge. The ball brushes the thigh pad before going to the keeper.
Overpitched, around off. Lees looks to drive but gets beaten by the slight inward movement and it takes the inside edge onto the pads.
Short in length, down the leg side. Alex is happy to leave it.
Length ball, angling way outside off. Lees shoulders arms to it.
Full ball, just outside off. Lees guides it through point to get off the mark.
Pitches it up, on off. Lees solidly blocks it.
Full and outside off, Lees pushes it to covers.
Length and way outside off. Lees shoulders arms to it.
Short of a length, angling down the leg side. Lees misses his flick.
A length ball, outside off, bit of away movement. Lees plays away from the body and taps it to point.

We are moments away from the start of the third Test match. West Indies players are out there in the middle. Alex Lees and Zak Crawley are the openers for England. Both teams take a knee in support of the Black Lives Matter movement. Now, Kemar Roach has a ball in his hand and Windies will look to take full advantage of any movement that is on offer on this pitch with the new ball. Here we go...

Pitch Report - Mark Butcher is near the pitch. He says there is a layer of green and bit of dampness and due to the cracks, the pitch might end up doing up and down. Informs there was some rain around. Adds that there will be sideways movement for the seamers.

Joe Root, the skipper of England, says that they have done lot of good stuff throughout the series and adds that they want to build from it. He mentions that every Test match one plays, one wants to contribute. He adds that their are some cracks in this pitch and hopes that it goes in their favour. He informs that their is one change in their team with Craig Overton replacing Matthew Fisher.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the skipper of West Indies, says they will bowl first. Explains that there is some moisture on the pitch and has a decent layer of grass. Tells the batting order has been showing good fight in each Test and he just wants to build a good foundation while batting. Informs there is one change as Kyle Mayers comes in for Veerasammy Permaul.

England (Playing XI) - Alex Lees, Zak Crawley, Joe Root (C), Dan Lawrence, Ben Stokes, Jonny Bairstow, Ben Foakes (WK), Chris Woakes, Craig Overton (In place of Matthew Fisher), Jack Leach, Saqib Mahmood.

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), John Campbell, Shamarh Brooks, Nkrumah Bonner, Jermaine Blackwood, Jason Holder, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Kyle Mayers (In place of Veerasammy Permaul), Kemar Roach, Jayden Seales, Alzarri Joseph.
TOSS - The coin goes up and lands in favour of West Indies. They have elected to BOWL first.

The skippers, Joe Root and Kraigg Brathwaite have dominated the batting department but it is harsh to blame the bowlers for it. The pitches have been pretty slow and low and bowlers from both teams have struggled to put pressure on the opposition’s batting lineup on a consistent basis. Saqib Mahmood had a debut to remember in the second Test and he might well be the x-factor England require with his extra pace to push for a result in this Test match. Jack Leach too has bowled well throughout the series while the Windies' bowling attack led by the experienced Kemar Roach also need to pull their socks coming into this final Test match. Will we see a result in the decider or this series will see yet another draw? We wait to find out. Stay tuned for the toss and other updates.

Hello and a warm welcome to the third and final Test match between England and West Indies. From Barbados, we move our attention to Grenada but still, it is hard to say which team has dominated the series so far. After two consecutive draws, the first thing viewers are hoping for is a pitch that will give some assistance to the bowler hence giving us an equal battle and a result to cheer.
... Day 1, Session 1...
We are back for the third innings! The players have made their way out to the middle. Alex Lees and Zak Crawley are at the crease. Kemar Roach will start proceedings with the ball. Let's go!
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

Right then! England have conceded a lead of 93 runs in the first innings and it is now onto their top order batters to make amends in the second innings. West Indies would be keen to make early inroads in the post-Lunch session. Do join us for the middle session which begins at 10.30 pm IST (5 pm GMT).

The man of the moment, Joshua Da Silva is down for a chat. He says that his emotions say it all about his century, tears came down immediately after his 100. Mentions that his family will be mighty pleased as they have always backed him, no matter what, and they will be happy watching him score this 100. States that he trusted Jayden Seales and Kemar Roach and without them, he wouldn't have got to his 100. Informs that he took his time and played his game, whenever he got a chance, he played the shots. Says that the pitch still has something in it for the bowlers.

West Indies did start well with the bat but once they lost their skipper, wickets kept tumbling for them and they lost the plot. Although, their lower order did a good job of hanging around with Joshua Da Silva and they now have a healthy lead of 93 runs. England were denied early breakthroughs but their bowlers came back well and it was Ben Stokes who got rid of the West Indies skipper. All the fast bowlers chipped in with wickets once England opened the floodgates. They were in a dominant position at one point but gave away the momentum and they were frustrated by the resistance that was displayed by the lower-order batters.

Well, it's been a long first session of Day 3, and West Indies will be mighty, mighty pleased with their batting performance here. Who would have thought that they would extend their lead till 93? But England can finally breathe a sigh of relief. A good fightback from the hosts, courtesy of a gutsy hundred from Joshua Da Silva. Windies were stuttering at 128/7 at one point but their lower order has done extremely well to ensure that they get a handy first innings lead. England would be a tad disappointed as they were bossing the game at one stage but have failed to capitalize on the momentum that they had.

OUT! CAUGHT AND BOWLED! Finally, England have wrapped the innings up! Joe Root comes back into the attack and gets the last wicket. This was a flighted delivery, very full, around middle. Jayden Seales chips it on the left of the bowler. Joe Root takes a sharp catch towards his left and above his head. West Indies are bundled out for 297, with a lead of 93 runs!
Commentary.Howout: c & b Joe Root

Commentary.Commentary: Flatter ball, on a length, around middle. Jayden Seales looks to defend but it takes the inside edge and goes towards square leg.
Loopy ball, on middle, fuller length. Jayden Seales leans and defends it out.

A fuller ball, around middle. Joshua Da Silva pushes it back to the bowler. Craig Overton collects the ball and throws it towards the stump at the striker's end. But it ends up hitting Joshua Da Silva on his pads. Craig Overton looks absolutely frustrated here!

NOT OUT! Joshua Da Silva had left the field as he thought he had nicked it but he has been called back now! Everything going West Indies' way! This was a length ball, outside off and jagging back in late. Joshua Da Silva looks to defend but the ball sneaks through his bat and pad and goes through to the keeper. England appeal for a caught behind and the umpire agrees. Joshua Da Silva opts for a review but he starts walking back to the pavilion as he thinks that he had hit that. The UltraEdge though shows that there was a clear daylight between bat and ball. The on-field decision has been overturned and Joshua Da Silva gets a life.

FOUR! Maiden Test hundred for Joshua Da Silva! He is absolutely ecstatic and this has been a top, top knock from the youngster! Another ball, back of a length, around middle. Joshua Da Silva stays back and whacks it through the mid on region for another boundary. A well-deserved century for West Indies' skipper.
FOUR! SMASHED! Joshua Da Silva moves to 96! Back of a length, around off. Joshua Da Silva hangs back and slaps it through the mid off region for a boundary.
Joshua Da Silva makes room on the off side, Craig Overton follows him with a short ball. Da Silva does well to cut it past point for a brace.
A well-directed bumper, around middle. Joshua Da Silva ducks underneath.
Craig Overton comes back to bowl. He replaces Joe Root!

DROPPED! A tough one for the silly point fielder though! Floated, full and outside off. Jayden Seales prods to block but the ball hits the splice of his bat and lobs up towards silly point. Dan Lawrence there, is a bit late to react and he puts it down.
Slower through the air, full and around off. Jayden Seales blocks it off the front foot.
Tossed up, on off. Jayden Seales keeps it out.
BEATEN! Flatter ball, outside off and turning in late. Jayden Seales tries to defend but the ball sneaks through his bat and pad.
SIX! BANG! Seales gets into the act now! Enough of blocking says Seales! This is tossed up, on middle. Jayden Seales lofts it way over long on and bags a maximum.
Tossed up, outside off. Jayden Seales defends it off the front foot.
This is a wayward ball, a high full toss, down leg. Joshua Da Silva sways away from the line of the delivery. The umpire doesn't call it wide.
Around off, kept out!
Looped up, on a length, around middle. Joshua Da Silva pushes it back to the bowler.
Floated, full and around leg. Joshua Da Silva keeps it out on the leg side.
Flatter and on a length, around leg. Jayden Seales looks to defend but it goes off the thick inside edge towards fine leg for a run.
An appeal for LBW but turned down! This is a flatter ball, going on with the angle from off. Jayden Seales looks to block but he misses and gets hit on his pad.
The skipper, Joe Root brings himself into the attack. Also, Lunch will be extended since West Indies are 9 down.

FOUR! Another boundary and with this Joshua Da Silva moves on to 90! Tad fuller now, around middle. Joshua Da Silva gets down on his knee and sweeps it past square leg for a boundary. And after 6 maiden overs, 10 runs comes off this one!
Drifting in, around middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva defends it out.

FOUR! Top shot! Finally, something for the fans to cheer about. It was a bit quiet out there! A shorter ball, spinning away, around off. Joshua Da Silva stays back and punches it past cover for a boundary.
Tad quicker and flatter, around middle. Joshua Da Silva defends it out.
Fuller again, around middle. Joshua Da Silva once again looks to go big but ends up dragging the ball towards square leg.

Well bowled! A fuller ball, this one lands around the leg pole and spins away. Joshua Da Silva clears his front foot and looks to heave this but the ball goes off the outside edge away from the keeper towards third man for two runs.
Craig Overton continues to bowl the shorter ball, outside off. Jayden Seales blocks it out. That's 6 maidens in a row!
Shorter ball once again, around off. Jayden Seales defends it out.
Shorter ball, down the leg side. Jayden Seales flicks it uppishly towards square leg and the fielder there collects it on the bounce.
Angling in, shorter ball, down the leg side. Jayden Seales tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Another back-of-a-length delivery, down the leg side. Jayden Seales misses his flick.
A shorter ball from 'round the wicket, outside off. Jayden Seales stays in his crease and taps it towards point.
Spinning away, outside off, fuller ball. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out. That's 5 maidens in a row now!
Quicker now, flatter again, around middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out towards mid-wicket.
Back of a length, down the leg side. Joshua Da Silva misses flick this time.
Flatter delivery, on middle. Joshua Da Silva defends it off the back foot.
Shorter ball, down the leg side. Joshua Da Silva leaves it alone.
Jack Leach comes over the wicket now, serves a fuller ball, on middle. Joshua Da Silva defends it out.
Shorter ball, outside off. Jayden Seales taps it towards gully.
Attacking the stumps, on a length. Jayden Seales defends it out.
Down the leg side, on a length. Jayden Seales misses his flick.
Angling in, around middle, on a good length. Jayden Seales tucks it towards mid-wicket.
A bouncer now, around middle. Jayden Seales ducks under it and lets that go through.
Fuller ball, around middle. Jayden Seales pushes it uppishly towards cover. The fielder there collects it on the bounce.
Outside off, touch fuller, spinning away. Joshua Da Silva pushes it towards point. Another maiden over by Jack Leach.
Fullish ball, flatter, around middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva tucks it towards square leg.
Loopy ball, full, around middle. Joshua Da Silva leans and defends it out.
Firing it down the leg side, tad fuller. Joshua Da Silva tucks it towards square leg.
Full, outside off. Joshua Da Silva pushes it cover.
Around middle, tad fuller. Joshua Da Silva defends it out.

In the air...and just short! A fuller ball, around middle. Jayden Seales chips it in the air towards mid on. Jack Leach there runs forward and puts in a dive but the ball lands just short of him there!
Outside off, on a length. Jayden Seales defends it out.
Well bowled! A yorker-length delivery, around middle. Jayden Seales does well to squeeze it out towards square leg.
Another length delivery, outside off. Jayden Seales blocks it out towards point.
Angling in, around middle, on a length. Jayden Seales looks to defend this but the ball goes off the outside edge towards the fielder at gully who collects the ball on a couple of bounces.
Shorter ball, around off. Jayden Seales looks to pull but he misses.
Jack Leach drops it short now, down the leg side. Joshua Da Silva looks to tuck this away but he misses. A maiden over by Jack Leach, which also means Jayden Seales will face the next over.
Loopy delivery, spins away, outside off. Joshua Da Silva presses forward and leaves it alone.
Tosses this one up, full, around middle. Joshua Da Silva leans and defends it out.
Flatter now, this one comes in with the angle, around the pads. Joshua Da Silva flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Another fuller ball, turning away, around off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out off the back foot.
Fuller ball, spinning away, around off. Joshua Da Silva stays in his crease and defends it out.
Down the leg side, fuller ball. Jayden Seales misses his flick.
Outside off, on a length. Jayden Seales defends it out towards point.
Short again, around off. Joshua Da Silva miscues his pull towards mid-wicket and rotates the strike this time
Back of a length, around middle. Joshua Da Silva pulls but the ball goes off the under-edge towards mid-wicket.
Much fuller now, around middle. Joshua Da Silva flicks it towards deep square leg. No run taken once again.
Shorter ball, around middle. Joshua Da Silva lifts it towards mid-wicket. The ball lands safely and deep mid-wicket will cut it out. No run taken!
Single from the last ball and he will retain the strike! A slightly shorter delivery, outside off. Joshua Da Silva cuts it to deep cover for a single.
Around off and slower in the air. Joshua Da Silva pushes it towards covers.
Loopy delivery and turning away from off. Joshua Da Silva dabs it to point.
Quicker and on off. Joshua Da Silva is solid on his defence.
A flatter delivery on middle. Joshua Da Silva goes deep in his crease and blocks it.
An appeal but the umpire turns it down. On middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva looks to paddle sweep it but misses. It is pitching outside leg as the replay confirms it. So good decision by the umpire.

Around off and slightly shorter. Joshua Da Silva chops it to backward point.

Tossed up on middle. Joshua Da Silva defends it off the front foot.
Goes shorter around off. Joshua Da Silva punches it back to the bowler.
Slower in the air, on middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it off the front foot.
On a length, on middle. Seales defends it towards the leg side.
Good-length delivery, around off. Seales looks to defend it from his crease. The ball straightens after pitching and beats the outside edge of his blade.
Takes a single on the fourth delivery! Short delivery on off again. Joshua Da Silva pulls it comfortably to deep square leg for a single.
Bangs this one short, on off. Joshua Da Silva sweeps it to deep square leg.
Goes fuller on off. Joshua Da Silva drives it to deep cover.
Lands on a length, on middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out.

Slower in the air, on middle. Joshua Da Silva shimmies down the track and goes for a big heave across the line. The ball goes off the inside half of his blade to the long on region and a single is taken to retain the strike.
Another fuller delivery on middle. Joshua Da Silva works it to mid-wicket.
Goes fuller on off. Joshua Da Silva works it to mid-wicket.
Dartes this on middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva goes back and defends it.
Another quicker and flatter delivery on middle. Joshua Da Silva pushes it towards the leg side.
A flatter delivery on middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out.

FOUR! More valuable runs for Windies! Lands a good-length delivery, around off. Seales looks to defend it from his crease. However, he gets a thick outside edge and the ball for goes left of second slip for a boundary.
Bangs this one short on middle. Joshua Da Silva pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Serves a length delivery, around off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out soldily.
Another length delivery on off. Joshua Da Silva defends it solidly.
Lands on a length, around off. Joshua Da Silva defends it off the front foot.
Back of a length, around leg. Joshua Da Silva pulls it to deep backward square leg. No run taken.

DRINKS! England started off well by grabbing an early wicket of Kemar Roach. They also missed out on a chance of getting the wicket of Jayden Seales, because they had no review left. But West Indies have done well to extend their lead by just over 50 runs. The partnership between Jayden Seales and Joshua Da Silva has also started to frustrate England. They will need to wrap this inning sup as fast as possible and not let West Indies get away with a big lead.
Slower in the air and angling into middle. Seales defends it off the front foot towards the leg side.
Slower in the air, around off. Joshua Da Silva skips down the track and works it to long on for a single. Again he has been given the single when he wanted it. Poor from England.
Slightly quicker and shorter on off. Joshua Da Silva goes back and punches it back to the bowler.
Flatter and fuller on middle. Joshua Da Silva goes for a sweep but gets the inside edge onto his pads. There is an appeal but clear bat there.
Another delivery that is on the shorter side, around off. Joshua Da Silva goes deep in his crease and punches it to deep point.
Starts with a slightly shorter delivery around off. Joshua Da Silva cuts it to deep cover.

Serves a length delivery, around off. Seales blocks it solidly from his crease.
Lands a length delivery on off. Seales defends it towards the leg side.
Goes fuller on middle. Joshua Da Silva flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Back of a length, on off. Joshua Da Silva pushes it back to the bowler.
Lands on a length, on middle. Joshua Da Silva works it to deep square leg. Again decide against taking a single.
Back of a length, on off. Joshua Da Silva punches it to long on but decides to not take a single.
Shaping away, outside off, on a length. Jayden Seales leaves it alone.
Back of a length, outside off. Jayden Seales pushes it towards cover off the back foot.
Much fuller now, around middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva works it away past mid-wicket and rotates the strike.
A full toss, around middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Another shorter ball, outside off. Joshua Da Silva walks across and pushes it towards gully.
Back of a length, outside off. Joshua Da Silva taps it towards point. No run taken there!
Good-length delivery, outside off. Jayden Seales leaves it alone.
Full in length, outside off. Jayden Seales drives it uppishly over the fielder at point. Two taken! West Indies have a lead of 50 runs now!
Fuller delivery, around off. Jayden Seales defends it out.
Much fuller, angling in, around middle and leg, slower as well. Joshua Da Silva flicks it past mid-wicket and rotates the strike.
Back of a length, outside off. Joshua Da Silva stays in his crease and defends it out.
Tad fuller, outside off. Joshua Da Silva leans and defends it out.
Outside off, shaping away, on a length. Jayden Seales leaves it alone.
Good-length delivery, on middle. Jayden Seales blocks it out solidly.
On a length, around middle. Jayden Seales blocks this but the ball goes off the toe-end and just misses the off pole.

Fuller now, around middle. Joshua Da Silva decides to take the aerial route now as he lifts it over the bowler's head. No timing on that shot though. Single taken!
Swing and a miss! Some extra bounce on this occasion! Shorter ball, outside off. Joshua Da Silva looks to slash this one but he misses.
Fraction shorter, around middle. Joshua Da Silva pulls and finds the fielder at mid-wicket.
Outside off, shaping away, on a length. Jayden Seales leaves it alone.
Tailing back in on a length, around middle. Jayden Seales blocks it out.
On a length, around middle. Joshua Da Silva works it away towards mid-wicket for a single. 250 up for West Indies!
Down the leg side, tad fuller. Joshua Da Silva misses his tuck.
Full, around middle. Joshua Da Silva pushes it back to the bowler.

FOUR LEG BYES! A huge shout for LBW, but the umpire says no! This one lands on a length, nips back in, around middle. Jayden Seales looks to block this but he misses. The ball deflects off his pads and goes towards third man for a boundary. England do not have a review left here! Oh, dear! The replay shows that it would have been out! Painful for England!
Change of length now! Much fuller on this occasion, around middle. Jayden Seales pushes it back to the keeper.
On a length, around middle. Jayden Seales defends it out solidly.
Another short ball now, nips back in a tad. Jayden Seales sways away and leaves it alone.
Back of a length, around middle and leg. Jayden Seales blocks it out.

Nipping away, around middle, fuller ball. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out.

Hello and welcome back, folks to the final Test of this entertaining series between West Indies and England. We are now heading towards Day 3 of this final Test which is known as the moving day and by the looks of it, we could probably get a result in this Test. Well maybe it’s too early to say that there is not much to differentiate between the two sides, but by the end of this moving day, we will surely get an idea of where the Test match is headed towards.

Right then, another riveting day of Test cricket comes to an end. The lead is now 28 for West Indies and Day 3 could well turn out to be a deciding day of this Test match. The first ball will be bowled at 7.30 pm IST (2.00 pm GMT). As you know, our coverage will start well in advance. So do join us for the same. Till then, goodbye and cheers!

Joshua Da Silva is up for a quick chat. He says his home form was not good but he is very happy today. Says that Alzarri Joseph and Roach played a good part to build a partnership and he feels their lower order can bat well. Tells that the pitch is flattened up, just some balls are staying low and hopes to bat the same way tomorrow and get as many runs as possible.

England, on the other hand, would feel that they should have done better post-Tea. They got 7 wickets in the first two sessions and would have fancied bundling out Windies quickly after Tea. However, by the time they got rid of Alzarri Joseph, West Indies were quite close to the English total and England failed to get any further breakthrough in the final session. Earlier, Woakes finally showed his class in the middle session with three crucial wickets to break the backbone of West Indies batting lineup. Stokes did what he is known to do and got two big breakthroughs when the partnership was building. However, just like Windies bowlers struggled in the final session on Day 1, English bowlers also failed to keep the intensity up in the final session and now need to take two wickets early on Day 3 to avoid West Indies take healthy first innings lead on this tricky pitch.

This has been quite an absorbing Test so far and after two days of Test cricket, there is nothing much to separate the two sides. The West Indies innings followed almost the same pattern of the England’s innings as middle-order failed to put up much resistance despite a decent opening partnership. However, much like England’s lower order, Windies' lower-order batters also contributed and Joshua Da Silva with his stellar technique is leading the way of the lower-order resilience. It has been a fine knock by the wicket-keeper batter and the Windies will hope that he can continue his good work on Day 3.

West Indies end Day 2 with a lead of 28 runs! Only one wicket in the final session after 7 wickets in the first two session and West Indies have their noses slightly ahead at the end of Day 2.
