Session 2, Overs - 26, Runs - 63, Wickets - 4. England bossing yet another session and it was Chris Woakes who ran through the Windies' middle-order lineup. He was low in confidence but this session will give him much more conviction after taking three wickets in his spell. Mayers was batting with intent but he gave away his wicket and England are three wickets away from bundling the host out. Joshua Da Silva and Alzarri Joseph need to steady the ship now.
Slower in the air, on middle. Joshua Da Silva leans forward and blocks it out quite solidly. At Tea on Day 2, West Indies are 134/7.
Quicker and flatter on off. Joshua Da Silva goes back and defends it towards the off side.
Again on the shorter side on middle. Joshua Da Silva goes back and works it towards the leg side.
Goes flatter and quicker on middle. Joshua Da Silva hangs back and blocks it out.
Slower in the air, around off. Joshua Da Silva defends it off the front foot.
Goes fuller on middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it off the front foot.
Might be the final over before Tea. It will be Jack Leach to bowl the final over before the break.
Goes fuller, around off. Alzarri Joseph drives it to covers.
Lands a length delivery on off. Alzarri Joseph defends it towards the off side.
Lands a length delivery on off. Alzarri Joseph blocks it out.
Back of a length and a bit of width provided this time. It shapes away a bit. Alzarri Joseph goes chasing for it but gets beaten.
Lands a length delivery on off. Alzarri Joseph defends it from his crease.
Goes fuller on middle. Joshua Da Silva works it towards the leg side.
Back of a length, on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out solidly off the back foot.
Saqib Mahmood is feeling his hamstring. Looks like he pulled it and is struggling a bit.
Back of a length, around off. Joshua Da Silva punches it to point.
Goes fuller but down the leg side. Joshua Da Silva looks to clip it but misses.
Back of a length, on middle. Joshua Da Silva works it towards mid-wicket.
Bangs this one short around leg. Alzarri Joseph ducks under it and the ball goes off the bounce to the keeper. He fails to collect it cleanly and the batters run a bye.

FOUR! Edge but just away from Root! Lands this just short of good length, outside off. Alzarri Joseph looks to push it towards the off side. However, the ball catches the outside edge of his blade and goes right of Root at first slip. He dives but fails to reach it and a boundary for Alzarri Joseph.
Lands on a  good length, around off. Joshua Da Silva defends it off the front foot.
Back of a length, on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out.
Back of a length, around off. Alzarri Joseph punches it to covers for a single.
Lands on a length, outside off. Alzarri Joseph leaves it alone.
Alzarri Joseph comes in now.

OUT! CAUGHT! Soft, soft dismissal for Kyle Mayers. He was looking so good out there but has to take a long walk back to the pavilion now. It is that man, Ben Stokes again, who breaks the partnership! A fullish delivery angling into middle and leg. Mayers looks to flick it away but is a tad early in his shot. The ball ends up looping up in the air towards mid on and Saqib Mahmood there takes an easy catch. England continue to chip in with wickets.
Commentary.Howout: c Saqib Mahmood b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, around off. Mayers defends it towards gully.
Slower in the air, on middle. Joshua Da Silva defends it off the front foot.
This is quicker and slightly shorter around off again. Joshua Da Silva hangs back and pushes it to covers.
Slightly shorter on off. Joshua Da Silva goes back and punches it to covers.
Joshua Da Silva skips down the track and pushes this full delivery back to Leach.
Quicker on off. Joshua Da Silva is solid on his front foot defence again.
Goes fuller on middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it off the front foot.
Goes slightly short on off. Mayers punches it to point.

FOUR! Streaky boundary! Stokes serves a good-length delivery, around off. Mayers looks to defend it off the front foot. The ball catches the outside edge of his blade and goes left of the first slip fielder for a boundary.
Goes fuller this time, around off. Mayers pushes it towards point.
Bangs this one short around off. Mayers defends it off the back foot. He was a bit surprised by the extra bounce but played it quite well in the end.
Goes slightly fuller on off. Mayers drives it to covers.
Lands on a length, on off. Mayers blocks it out.
Ben Stokes is back on.
Review! England take a review for LBW. UltraEdge shows no bat involved. Ball Tracking shows pitching outside leg. The on-field decision stays.

NOT OUT! Leach darts this around leg. Joshua Da Silva goes for a sweep but misses. The ball hits his pads and there is a huge appeal. The umpire though is unmoved. England take a review. The replay rolls in and the Ball Tracker shows that it is pitching outside leg. So the original decision stays and England lose their review. Joshua Da Silva will continue.
Slightly shorter around off. Joshua Da Silva punches it to covers.
FOUR! Great use of the depth of the crease! Short and wide outside off. Joshua Da Silva goes back and cuts it through backward point for a boundary.
Goes fuller on middle. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out.
On the pads. Joshua Da Silva just left of short leg this time.
Slower in the air, on off. Joshua Da Silva leans forward and blocks it.
Goes fuller around leg. Joshua Da Silva works it to fine leg for a single.
On a length, on middle. Joshua Da Silva works it to mid-wicket.
Serves a good-length delivery on off. Joshua Da Silva is solid in his defence.
Lands a length delivery on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out.
This is full and down the leg side. Joshua Da Silva looks to clip it away but misses.
Drifting on the pads. Mayers looks to clip it away but misses. The ball hits his pads and goes towards square leg and a leg bye is taken.
A flatter delivery on off. Joshua Da Silva rocks back and works it to mid-wicket.
Slower in the air, on middle. Joshua Da Silva defends it towards short leg.
A fuller delivery on middle. Mayers pushes it to long on for a single.
Tossed up delivery on off. Mayers drives it to mid off.
A fuller delivery, outside off. Mayers goes for a big booming drive but misses.
Down the leg side first up from Leach. Joshua Da Silva looks to sweep but misses. The ball brushes his pads and goes behind the stumps for a leg bye. A stifled appeal but no damage done.
Jack Leach to bowl now.
FOUR! Second boundary in the over! Overton continues with the short stuff and Mayers takes him on. This is short angling into the body. Mayers pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a boundary.
Back of a length, around off. Mayers punches it to covers.
Goes shorter around off again. Mayers rides the bounce and defends it towards the off side.
Lands on a length, around off. Mayers dabs it towards point off the front foot.
Another short delivery and around off. Mayers sways away from the line of the ball.

FOUR! Not where, he wanted to hit it but still Mayers will take this with both hands! A short delivery, outside off. Mayers looks to pull it but the ball hits probably the lower part of his blade and goes past mid off for a boundary.
A good-length delivery on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it off the front foot.
Serves a length delivery on off. Joshua Da Silva leans forward and defends it.
Back of a length, on middle. Joshua Da Silva works it right of square leg and looks for a single but is sent back by his partner.
Lands on a length, on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it solidly off the front foot.
Fullish delivery on middle. Joshua Da Silva drives it off the inner half of his blade towards the leg side.

Back of a length, on off. Mayers defends it towards the off side and sets off for a single. The fielder comes charging in and has a shy at the batter's end. Luckily for Joshua Da Silva, he misses and a single is completed.
Saqib Mahmood to continue.
Short of a length, on off. Da Silva punches off the back foot to mid off.
On middle, this is nudged to short mid-wicket.
Da Silva called for a single but the fielder was too close to him! Length and on middle. Da Silva tucks it to square leg.
Fuller and on off. Mayers taps it to covers for a quick single.
Short of a length, on middle. Mayers miscues the pull shot completely and the ball drops on the deck.
A length ball, angling on middle, this is hit to square leg.
Craig Overton (8-0-35-1) is back on.
A length ball, outside off, it nips away a touch. Da Silva prods to defend but it takes the outside edge and goes to gully where the fielder collects it on a bounce.
Short and on off. Da Silva pulls it along the ground to mid-wicket.
On the pads, flicked to square leg.
Mahmood mixing his lengths! This is around off, on a length. Da Silva tucks it to square leg.
Very full and on middle. Da Silva squeezes it out to mid on.
A length ball, outside off, nips back in and does not bounce much, Da Silva shoulders arms to it.

Drinks! English bowlers have taken the momentum of the second-half of the first session into this post-Lunch session and have bowled with some great plans and accuracy. Chris Woakes seems to have finally arrived on the Caribbean shores as he bowled his heart out to take three wickets in this hour of play. Windies have lost the cream of their batting lineup and it is upto their lower-order now to bail them out of trouble. West Indies still trail by 98 runs and they need a partnership now to bring some stability back into this innings.

SIX! Short in length, outside off. Mayers stands tall and pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a biggie. The TV umpire wanted to take a quick look at whether it went over the ropes or not and the result is maximum.
Length and on off. Kept out.
A short ball that does not bounce much. Mayers dodges under it without watching the ball.
Length ball, this one nips back in sharply. Mayers defends it right under his eyes.
Length and on off. Mayers blocks it out.
FOUR! A length ball, from around the wicket, around off. Mayers guides it with soft hands and through gully for a boundary. 100 up for West Indies!
This one jags back in, on middle. Da Silva dead bats it.
Full and on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Fuller and dies off the deck, on middle. Da Silva flicks it to short mid-wicket. There are two short mid-wicket fielders standing side-by-side to each other.
A length ball, on off. Da Silva defends on the front foot.
Angling on the pads, Da Silva wrists it to square leg.
Length and on middle. Defended out.
Short of a length, on middle, pulled to square leg for a single.
Fuller and on middle. Da Silva leans and blocks it.
Joshua Da Silva is the next man in.

OUT! LBW! Jermaine Blackwood takes the review as he is given LBW! UltraEdge shows no bat there. Ball Tracking shows umpire's call on wickets hitting and another one bites the dust. Coming to the ball - This was on a length and straying around middle and leg, there was extra bounce as well. Jermaine Blackwood misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. An appeal and up goes the finger. Jermaine Blackwood takes the review thinking that the bounce will save him but the ball was going onto hit the top of leg pole. West Indies are still 109 runs behind.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Chris Woakes

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! In the air and through the gap! Shorter in length and outside off. Blackwood flashes his blade at it. A thick outside edge and the ball fly past the diving gully fielder for a boundary.
This one stays low, on a length and on middle. Blackwood does well to defend it out.
A length ball, on off. Mayers knocks it towards covers for a quick single.

Dropped! Short in length, outside off, extra bounce there. Blackwood looks to shoulders arms to it but the ball goes off the bottom half of the bat and to the keeper. Ben Foakes has to be quick to take this to his right as the ball was dying all the time but fumbles and fails to catch it. Was a bit wrong-footed as well.
A length ball, straying on middle. Blackwood turns it to mid-wicket.
On the pads, this is nudged to the left of deep square leg and the batters take a couple of runs.
A length ball, on off, nips back in. Blackwood blocks it out.
This time he flicks it in the gap, towards deep square leg for a couple of runs.

Just short of the fielder! So close! A fuller ball, tailing around middle and leg. Blackwood is a touch early as he looks to flick and he chips it towards short mid-wicket where the fielder dives forward but it falls short of him.
Saqib Mahmood (8-5-14-1) is back into the attack.
A length ball, on off. Mayers defends with his bat and pad together. Good over from Chris Woakes!
Length and outside off. Kyle leaves it lone.
Wide! A pacy short ball, on middle. Mayers evades it but the umpire gives a wide for a height.
Almost chopped on! Back of a length and slanting around off. Mayers tries to defend away from the body and it takes the inside edge and bounces past the off stump.
Length and on middle. Mayers defends it late and to mid-wicket.
On a length and around off. Mayers hops and keeps it out on the off side.
Length ball, angling outside off. Left alone.
Short of a length, on middle. Mayers is hurried as he pulls it to square leg. The batters take a single.
Touch fuller and angling on off. Defended out.
A length ball, on off. Mayers works it to covers.
Around off, on a length. Blackwood drops it in front of covers for a quick single.
Stokes serves a short ball, around off. Blackwood sits under it.
Back of a length, around leg. Mayers pulls it to fine leg for a single.
Kyle Mayers is the next man in.

OUT! TAKEN! Two wickets in the over for Chris Woakes! It is the short ball again, around off. Holder looks to pull but he is not in much control of his shot. The ball takes the top edge of his blade and goes high in the sky and towards deep square leg where Jonny Bairstow charges forward and takes it. A two-wicket maiden over by Chris Woakes. This over will give him a lot of confidence going ahead in this Test match and even further.
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b Chris Woakes

Commentary.Commentary: A length ball, on middle. Holder blocks it out.
Back of a length, around off. Holder blocks it off the back foot.
Jason Holder walks in at number 6.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! The short ball continues to give England rewards and this wicket will do so much for Chris Woakes who was struggling a bit. This is short and on middle. Bonner sees it and ducks under it but keeps his bat hanging horizontally out. The ball takes the gloves and goes to the keeper, Ben Foakes who pouches it. England right on top at the moment.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Chris Woakes

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, on off. Bonner is solid as he defends it on the surface.
A length ball, outside off, tailing back in slightly. Bonner shoulders arms to it.
Length and on middle. Blocked to mid-wicket.
Another short ball, on middle. Blackwood bends his back and sways away from it.
Short of a length, on middle. Blackwood sits under it.
Fuller ball, on middle. Blackwood looks to drive through covers but mistimes it to mid on.
Bangs a short ball, on middle. Bonner mistimes it and hits it aerially but well wide of the fielder standing in front of square. A single taken.
A length ball, on off. Bonner prods and defends it out.

Ohh...nicely bowled! After bowling away going deliveries in this over, Woakes brings this one back into the batter. Lands on a length, on off and it nips back in. Bonner defends it off the inside half of his blade towards fine leg for a single.
Serves a good-length delivery, outside off. Bonner lets it go.
Much better! Lands on a length but around off this time. Bonner presses forward to defend it towards the off side.
Another delivery on a length, it is outside off and Bonner leaves it alone.
Lands on a length, on off. Bonner defends it watchfully.
Back of a length, around off. Bonner lets it go.
Back of a length, on off. Jermaine Blackwood goes back and punches it back to the bowler. There seems a definite plan from the English bowlers to bowl short.
Goes for a short delivery and it is angled into the body. Jermaine Blackwood ducks under it.
Back of a length and down the leg side. Jermaine Blackwood lets it go.
A good-length delivery, outside off. Jermaine Blackwood leaves it alone.
Goes fuller on middle. There is a bit of inswing there. Jermaine Blackwood defends it towards the leg side.
Back of a length, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood rides the bounce and works it towards mid-wicket.
Woakes goes wide of his crease and angles this on middle and leg. Jermaine Blackwood works it towards square leg for a single.
Back of a length, on off. Jermaine Blackwood goes back and blocks it out.
Drifts on middle and leg. Bonner clips it to fine leg for a single.
Fuller delivery on off. Bonner leans forward and blocks it.
Review! West Indies take a review for caught behind. UltraEdge confirms that the ball took the thigh pad rather than the bat and the decision is changed.

NOT OUT! Woakes serves a length ball down the leg side. Bonner looks to clip it but misses. The ball goes back to the keeper and English players appeal straightaway. The umpire also reviews it. However, Bonner reviews it straightaway and the UltraEdge confirms that the ball has hit his pad and not his bat. So the decision will be overturned and Bonner survives.
Very full delivery on off at 137 kph. Bonner drives it to mid on.
Lands on a length and it is outside off. Easy leave for Jermaine Blackwood.
A fullish delivery on off at 135 kph. Jermaine Blackwood drives it to covers.
Goes fuller on middle and leg. Jermaine Blackwood flicks it to deep backward square leg for a couple.
Adjusts his length and serves a length ball, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood defends it towards the leg side.
FOUR! This time, Jermaine Blackwood puts it away! It is a half-volley on off. Jermaine Blackwood drives it past mid off for a boundary. Good shot, they need to be positive on this uneven turf.
Stokes starts with a full toss on off. Jermaine Blackwood drives it to mid off.
Lands on a length, on middle. Bonner defends it off the front foot towards mid on. Good over by Woakes.
Goes fuller on off. Bonner drives it to mid off.
Back of a length, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood works it to fine leg for a single.

England lose their review! This is a length delivery and down the leg side. Jermaine Blackwood looks to clip it away but misses. The ball brushes the thigh pad and pad on its way and Ben Foakes takes a good grab to his left. English players appeal but the umpire turns it down. They take a review and the UltraEdge confirms no bat involved. So the original decision stays and Jermaine Blackwood will continue.

That's better! It's more like a Chris Woakes, we all know. Lands on a good length, around off and it shapes back in. Jermaine Blackwood lets it go through to the keeper but it was pretty close to the stumps.
Starts with a back-of-a-length delivery on off. Jermaine Blackwood hangs back and blocks it.
We are back for the second session. The players are out in the middle. Jermaine Blackwood and Nkrumah Bonner to resume their batting. Chris Woakes to start for England.
... Day 2, Session 2...

West Indies will be disappointed after the start they got. Kraigg Brathwaite, probably the best batter of West Indies got out after a good start. The disappointment continued for Campbell as he too got yet another good start but failed to continue the momentum. The pitch started to open up and it became difficult to bat on as the game progressed. There was bounce occasionally and sometimes the ball stayed too low which was seen in this session. It seems like the pitch will stay the same in the afternoon session which will begin at 10.10 pm IST (4.40 pm GMT) and West Indies will have to be extremely careful as they look to do the repair work. Do join us for the post-Lunch session.

Session 1, Overs 25 - Runs - 71, Wickets- 3. The tourist will be the happier side going into the break. The first hour of play did not create much chances as England were inconsistent with their lines and lengths but all of a sudden things changed as the lines were much short and there was much more intent. Stokes and Mahmood got assistance from the pitch as the ball stayed low while Overton targeted the body of Campbell and twice struck him on the helmet and eventually got his wicket. One thing is, the pitch is still helping the bowlers and England will love to replicate the same in the next session.

A peach of a delivery to end the first session on Day 2! Lands it on a good length, around off. Bonner looks to defend it off the front foot. However, the ball comes sharply into the batter and beats the inside edge of Bonner's blade. It goes over the stumps back to the keeper. No damage done in the end and at Lunch on Day 2, West Indies are 71/3.
Pulls his length back, outside off. Bonner lets it go.
Nice full delivery on middle. Hint of shape into the batter. Bonner pushes it towards the leg side.
Goes slightly fuller on off. Bonner blocks it off the front foot.
Lands on a length, on off. Bonner defends it towards the off side.
Saqib Mahmood continues with the short stuff. Angles this into the body. Bonner takes his bottom hand off and defends it towards the leg side.
Another short delivery angling into the body. Bonner pulls it to fine leg for a single.
Short and down the leg side this time, Bonner lets it go through to the keeper.
Back of a length, angling into the body. Bonner nudges it to short fine leg as he is slightly hurried by that shorter length delivery.
Back of a length, around leg. Bonner looks to pull it but the ball hits him high on the body.
Back of a length, around off. Jermaine Blackwood steers it to third man for a single.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! John Campbell after doing all the hardwork departs as he gets strangled down the leg side. Back of a length, around leg. John Campbell looks to clip it but gets a glove on it. Ben Foakes moves to his right and dives to take a good catch. England appeal but the umpire seems not interested. They go for a review and the UltraEdge confirms that the ball has brushed the gloves on its way. So the decision will be overturned and John Campbell has to walk back disappointed.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Craig Overton

Commentary.Commentary: Jermaine Blackwood walks out to the middle.
Review taken! England take a review for caught behind. UltraEdge shows a spike as there was some glove on it. The on-field decision is overturned.
WIDE! Bouncer from 'round the wicket on middle. John Campbell ducks under it, The umpire calls it wide for height.
This time a bit straighter, on off. Bonner is solid in his front foot defence.
Continues with a good-length delivery, outside off. Bonner lets it go again.
Serves a good-length delivery, outside off. Bonner shoulders his arms yet again.
Lands on a length, around off. Bonner leaves it alone.
Nkrumah Bonner is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! Another wicket for England, courtesy of a delivery that keeps low. Saqib Mahmood lands it on a length, on middle and it keeps low as Brooks looks to clip it but misses. The ball hits his pads and Saqib Mahmood starts celebrating immediately. He turns back to the umpire eventually to appeal and the umpire raises his finger. Brooks has a chat with John Campbell but decided against taking a review and suddenly two wickets for England and this kind of uneven bounce will put doubts in the mind of the incoming batters.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Saqib Mahmood

Commentary.Commentary: Lands on a length, around off. Brooks defends it towards the off side.
The physio is out and is having a quick conversation with John Campbell. Reminder, he got struck twice on the helmet.
Another short ball on middle. John Campbell looks to pull but is beaten this time.

Goes short on middle. John Campbell pulls it to deep mid-wicket and tries to come back for the second. The throw from the deep is bit wide and Craig Overton direct it towards the stumps using his hand. However, the batter is safe and the replays confirm it as the on-field umpire takes it upstairs. Two runs taken.
Tight run! Back of a length, on middle. Brooks turns it right of mid-wicket for a quick single.
FOUR! Nicely played! Overpitched delivery on off. Brooks leans forward and creams a drive past mid off for a boundary.
On the shorter side, around off. Brooks lets it go this time.
Back of a length, on middle. John Campbell works it through mid-wicket for a single.
Goes fuller on middle. Brooks leans forward and drives it to mid on.
Pulls his length back a bit, outside off. Brooks lets it go.
Lands on a length, on off. Brooks defends it off the front foot solidly.
Another short ball around leg. Brooks ducks under it again.
Bangs this one short and it is down the leg side. Brooks ducks under it and Ben Foakes dives to his left to stop it.
Back of a length, on middle. Brooks works it to deep mid-wicket for a couple.
A length ball, outside off. Campbell punches off the back foot to point.
Length and on the pads, flicked to square leg for a single.
Both the batters are taking some body blows now. Short of a length, on off. Brooks looks to leave it but the ball nips back in and stays low to hit him around the waist area.
Fuller and on off, pushed to covers.
FOUR! Fuller and angling on middle. Brooks wrists it through mid-wicket for a boundary. Lovely shot.
John Campbell has been hit again on his helmet. The physio is out for mandatory concussion test again and John Campbell looks fine. This will unsettle him a bit.

Leg bye! Campbell again gets hit on the helmet. Short and targeting the body. Campbell looks to sway away but is late in his process and gets hit on the helmet. The ball rolls to square leg for a leg bye. A concussion protocol coming up. A fist bump between him and Overton as Campbell looks okay.
Another solid block from Shamarh Brooks to end the over.
Much better line from Mahmood! Length and just outside off. Brooks again tries to defend inside the line, he misses.
Length ball, around off. Kept out.
Shorter and on off. Brooks defends on his toes.
Length ball, on middle. Brooks wrists it to mid-wicket.
A length ball, tight around off. Brooks looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.

John Campbell has been hit on his helmet! Time for mandatory concussion test. The substitute fielder runs in and brings with him few new helmets. John Campbell is now putting a new helmet on. The physio reckons he is fine and is ready to resume.

Ohh...that is nasty! A short ball, cross-seam delivery and this one does not bounce much as John Campbell expected. He bends his back and looks to sit under it but gets hit on the grill of the helmet. Craig Overton was quick to show his sympathy.
Angling on the pads, Brooks tickles it to fine leg off the inside edge for a single. He is off the mark.
Another solid block by Brooks as this was on a length and on off.
Fullish ball, outside off. Brooks gets his bat down to defend it.
On a length, around off Brooks keeps it out on the off side.
A  length ball, outside off. Campbell punches it through covers for a single.
Shamarh Brooks walks in at number 3.

OUT! LBW! Ben Stokes knew it as soon as this one rapped on the pads and he didn't even bother to turn for the appeal. A length ball, around off, this one nips back in off the surface and stays low off the deck as well. Brathwaite hangs back to defend but gets beaten by the stir of the ball. An appeal and up goes the finger. A huge, huge wicket as Kraigg Brathwaite was the most effective batsman in the whole series till now for West Indies, goes back early.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, outside off, stays a touch low. Brathwaite plays it late and drops his bat.
Length and on off, this is worked to covers.
Very full and angling on the pads. Campbell bunts it to square leg for a single. 50 up for West Indies.
On a length and outside off. Campbell punches it to covers.
Fuller ball, drifting on off. Campbell defends with soft hands to the leg side.
Better as Overton targets the middle stump. Brathwaite keeps it out.
Down the pads again. This is flicked to square leg for a couple of runs. Easy for West Indies to rotate the strike.
Shorter and on the hips. Brathwaite clips it to deep square leg for an easy couple.
This one comes with the angle around the 5th stump channel. Brathwaite offers no shot.
Length ball, around middle, tucked to mid-wicket.
FOUR! A loosener to start with! Too full, and down the leg side. Brathwaite looks to flick but gets an inside edge and past the diving keeper for a boundary.

Drinks! This has been quite a solid start for the West Indies. The first hour of the day was always going to be crucial and both the Windies openers have negotiated the new ball with good application and organised technique. England bowlers, on the other hand, have been inconsistent in their lines and lengths and have failed to put pressure on the batters. England need wickets here as they don’t have lot of runs to work with and the conditions are likely to improve for batting as the ball gets softer and the sun beats down. Craig Overton (3-0-9-0) is back into the attack.
Pitched up, on middle. Campbell defends it on the front foot.
Length ball, slanting on middle. Campbell turns it to mid off.
This is outside off. Left alone.
A length ball, on off. Campbell defends it to covers. He wanted a quick single but Brathwaite wasn't ready. No harm done.
Slides a full ball, way down the leg side. Campbell misses his flick.
Too straight on the pads, flicked wide of square leg for a couple of runs.
Length and on middle. Defended out.
This one moves away after landing but the line was outside off. Brathwaite shoulders arms.

Leg bye! Strays it down on the pads. Campbell misses his flick. It goes off the pads and to fine leg for a leg bye.
On the pads, flicked through mid-wicket for a single.

Length ball, around off. Brathwaite stays back as he defends it to covers.

Slightly shorter on middle. John Campbell works it to square leg.
Closer to the off pole and on a length. John Campbell leans forward and defends it towards the off side.
Fullish delivery, outside off again. John Campbell shoulders his arms again.
Angles this across the batter. It is full and outside off. John Campbell leaves it alone.

Nice delivery, Lands on a good length, on middle and it shapes into the batter. John Campbell defends it off the inner half of his blade towards square leg.
Very full, on off with a bit of away swing at 133 kph. Kraigg Brathwaite digs it out to point.
This time it is bit fuller and outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite leans forward and lets it go.
Serves a good-length delivery, around off at 137 kph. Kraigg Brathwaite blocks it out.
Lands on a good length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite leaves it alone and the ball goes off the bounce to the keeper.

On a good length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite with a good leave again.

On a good length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite shoulders his arms again.

We are back for the final innings of this Test! The players have made their way out to the middle. John Campbell and Kraigg Brathwaite are at the crease. Chris Woakes will start with the ball. Here we go...
... Fourth innings ...

It has been another dismal batting performance from England. Their dependence on their skipper, Joe Root was exposed yet again as none of their batters managed to get in and score big. For West Indies, it was the game-changing spell of Kyle Mayers that completely turned the game in Windies' favor. All their bowlers stuck to their task and have ensured that they don't have a mountain to climb in the fourth innings.

So England have only managed to add only 17 more runs to their overnight score. West Indies now need just 28 runs to seal the series now and it should be a cakewalk for them. The Windies bowlers have made sure that the English tail doesn't wag as it did in the first innings. It was Kemar Roach who picked up the remaining two wickets and England now are on the brink of a series defeat.
Review! West Indies have opted for a review for caught behind! The UltraEdge rolls in and it shows a clear spike as the ball passes the bat. The on-field decision needs to be overturned.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Kemar Roach wraps the innings up and Jack Leach fails to survive this time! A fuller ball, outside off, shapes away a tad. Jack Leach looks to push this but manages to get a slight outside edge back to the keeper. Joshua Da Silva takes a good low catch. However, the umpire thinks otherwise and gives it not out. But West Indies opt for a review! The replay does show a spike as the ball passes through the bat and the on-field decision has been overturned. England are all out for 120 and West Indies need 28 runs to win this Test as well as the series.
Commentary.Howout: c Joshua Da Silva b Kemar Roach

England have lost their ninth wicket now.

We are set for Day 4 to get underway! The players have made their way out to the middle. Chris Woakes and Jack Leach are at the crease. Jayden Seales will start proceedings with the ball. Let's go!

PITCH REPORT - Mark Butcher and Steven Harmison are near the pitch. The former says that the cracks have opened up a bit and there can be some variable bounce. Harmison says that hitting the right areas is key on this pitch. Butcher says that the pitch hasn't deteriorated much and it has been dry since Day 1.

West Indies have been bossing the game so far and they will be keen to wrap things up early on in the first session of Day 4. Kyle Mayers picked wickets for fun on Day 3 and West Indies require two more wickets to bowl out the opposition. England lead by just 10 runs and they would hope that their tail-enders, along with Chris Woakes stretch the lead as far as possible and give their bowlers something to play with in the last innings. The English side has a tough task in front of them and it is West Indies who are on the brink of clinching the Richards-Botham Trophy. Stay tuned as the live action begins shortly.

Hello and a very warm welcome to the coverage of Day 4 of the final Test match between England and West Indies. This could also turn out to be the last day of this enthralling Test series, unless we see the English tail-enders repeating their heroics of the first innings.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Right then! Another intriguing day of Test cricket comes to an end. England's lead is just 10 runs in the second innings, and they have only two wickets in hand to extend their lead. West Indies will be smelling victory from here and will be looking to wrap things up as soon as possible in the first session on Day 4. The first ball of Day 4 will be bowled at 7.30 pm IST (2.00 pm GMT). As you know, our build-up will start well in advance. So do join us for the same. Till then, goodbye and cheers!

Kyle Mayers is up for a quick chat. He says that his performance is very special for him. Mentions that straighter deliveries were working for him with variable bounce and movement and he just wanted to make the batters play as much as possible. Informs that Joshua Da Silva's innings was very special, and it was very emotional for him also. Says that he just waited for his turn to play and the opportunity turned in and he grabbed it.

Earlier in the day, it was the pair of Jayden Seales and Joshua Da Silva who frustrated the English bowlers as they stitched together a partnership of 52 runs for the last wicket and ensured that they get a healthy lead. Joshua Da Silva registered his maiden Test hundred, which is also turning out to be a match-winning one for the Windies. Then it was their bowlers, especially Kyle Mayers who kept the English batters on their toes and it was Mayers' spell that completely shifted the match in West Indies' favor. Apart from Alex Lees and Jonny Bairstow, no other batter managed to get into double figures for England, and they now find themselves in deep, deep trouble heading into Day 4.

Well, Day 3 of a Test match is said to be a moving day and this Test has moved at a rate of knots, courtesy of some fine bowling performance from West Indies! They have completely dominated Day 3 and are on the brink of a Test series win heading into Day 4. England's batting woes continued in their second innings and they have only themselves to blame. Kyle Mayers has been the star performer for the Windies and his inclusion in this Test match has turned out to be a terrific decision.

But the ball goes off the outside edge and straight towards Jason Holder at gully. He juggles at first but holds onto it in the end. England are now 8 down.

Right then! West Indies still lead by 50 runs. They will look to pick the remaining 6 wickets as early as possible. Things are a little tough for England but for now, they need to rebuild and Alex Lees and Jonny Bairstow need to stick around till the end of the day at least. We have an exciting final session coming up which begins at 12:30 am IST (7:00 pm GMT, previous day). Stay tuned!

West Indies bowlers are breathing fire at the moment, Kyle Mayers, in particular. Jayden Seales began the proceedings by grabbing the wicket of Zak Crawley, and since then it's been only Kyle Mayers leading the charge. He was been very disciplined with his bowling and has been rewarded with three wickets. Coming into this session West Indies were in a comfortable position but at the end of this session, they are in a commanding position. Top-order of England has failed once again. However, Alex Lees is the batter who is at the crease since the very first over, he is looking settled for now but he will want to carry on till the end of the day along with Jonny Bairstow at the other end. England trail only by 50 runs, but it still feels a long way to go for them. We did witness the lower-order of England chipping in with vital runs at the end of the first innings, so they do have batting left but they cannot afford to lose more wickets.

What a session this has been for West Indies! A lead of 93 was always looking tough for England. The hosts are well in control of this game, whereas England are not having the best day in the office! They will be disappointed with their effort with the bat thus far.

But the cricketing action does not stop here. You can switch tabs and enjoy our coverage from the Indian T20 League, where Bangalore is taking on Punjab. See you there, folks!

Joe Root, the skipper of England, says that it has been a frustrating Test match, they showed a lot of fire in the first innings. Adds that Day 3 was a very frustrating day for them, as they didn't manage it well. Mentions that they took a few strides forward in the first two games, but he credits West Indies for the way they played this match. Informs that they didn't read the surface, as well as they should have. States that there is still a lot of learning that needs to be done. Adds that Jack Leach has been exceptional and Dan Lawrence also showed a lot of promise, which is very exciting. Concludes by thanking all the fans who came out and supported them.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the victorious skipper is also the PLAYER OF THE SERIES. He says that it feels fantastic to win the series and he thanks all the fans for coming to the stadium and supporting them. Adds that he has been working hard and it is pleasing that he is getting rewards now. Tells that everyone has chipped in at some point and it has been a total team effort. Applauds all his teammates by saying that they have been brilliant. He adds that they had a camp before the series and they ensured that they practiced hard and were aware that this was going to be an important series for them. Tells that the young players in the side are willing to learn and players like Joshua Da Silva, Jayden Seales, and Alzarri Joseph have done really well in this Test series. Mentions that they want to build on this performance and they cannot afford to relax going forward. Says that all the players will need to stay hungry and prepare well for their next series.

Joshua Da Silva is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH. He says that he has dreamt of getting a hundred and he is very happy with his performance. Adds that all the credit goes to his batting partners and it was because of them that he was able to get his hundred. Tells that keeping wickets on this track was a challenge and he will take a lot of learnings from this series. Mentions that he will look to improve and keep getting better game-by-game.

England tried their best, fought hard, but failed in the end. They struggled while batting in both the innings. Their top-order and middle-order failed to score runs, and had it not been for their lower-order, England would have not reached their respectable total of 204 in the first innings. Their bowlers did a fine job at the beginning, but they let West Indies get away at the end, and coming to bowl for the second time, they had very little to fight for. A disappointing tour for them, but still a few positives to take from this tour. Jack Leach finished with 11 wickets in this series, Ben Stokes also displayed his skills in this series.  However, before this tour, they made a bold decision of leaving out Stuart Broad and James Anderson, and that might have hurt them in hindsight. Nevertheless, a lot to think about for England.

We witnessed a run-fest in the previous two Test matches, but this time things were a bit different. West Indies bowlers were right on cue. They displayed their magic in the first innings by dismissing England for 204 runs and they did the same thing in the third innings as well. They made sure that England do not get away with a healthy lead and they bundled out England for 120, the second time. Kyle Mayers was the leader of the pack, he grabbed his maiden five-wicket haul and demolished England's batting line-up. Not to forget Joshua Da Silva's maiden Test hundred which helped West Indies get to 297 while batting. All in all, it's been a sensational performance from the hosts and they have come out on top eventually.

West Indies win, and they win in an emphatic style! The Richards-Botham trophy will stay with West Indies. After two hard-fought draws, we finally get a result in this match. West Indies have given a lot to cheer about to their fans at Grenada. While England have now lost yet another Test series. A lot to ponder for them now. The players of West Indies take a lap of honor to acknowledge the fans that have cheered them from the stands.
